## Overview
Participatory Action Research (PAR) is a collaborative research approach that actively involves community members in all stages of the research process.

## Purpose
The purpose of PAR is to enhance the relevance and effectiveness of research endeavors by involving community members in the research process, promoting ownership, building trust, generating rich data, and facilitating empowerment.

## How it works
PAR follows a cyclical process of inquiry, action, and reflection, often involving multiple iterations. It involves engaging community stakeholders, identifying needs and challenges, co-designing solutions, implementing actions, and reflecting and refining iteratively.

## Requirements
To effectively use PAR for R&D, the following are needed: strong community engagement skills, understanding of local context and needs, resources for collaboration and action, capacity for iterative reflection and adaptation, and a supportive organizational culture and structures.

## Reflections
When using PAR for R&D purposes, it is essential to well-capture participation from key stakeholders, engage stakeholders at different levels, use only the necessary steps, focus on problem, context, and solution recommendations, and be aware of the limitations and potential biases of the approach.
